\pard\fi720\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx9291 JOHANN CAREFULLY PLACED eightthintwigsinthe cake. He inspected his creation a final time, gently chastising himself for the messiness of the inscription, and then lit the makeshift candles with a small hand torch.\par
\pard\fi720\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx9291\ldblquote You may open your eyes now,\rdblquote  Johann said to Maria as he carried the cake into their cave.\par
The girl\rquote s face broke into a dazzling smile. She rose from the chair where she had been sitting and bounded toward Johann. He bent down and held the cake, which he had made from the fruits and berries on the island, directly in front of her eyes.\par
\ldblquote Happy Birthday to you... Happy Birthday to you, Johann sang. In the ffickering light from the candles he could see Maria beaming with joy.\par
When the song was over, the little girl blew vigorously across the top of the cake. All but two of the twigs stopped burning immediately The sudden burst of smoke, how\f1\-\f0 ever, made Johann cough. Laughing, and moving away from the smoke, he put the cake down on the small table next to their mats. Maria ran over and threw her arms around his waist.\par
\ldblquote Thank you, Johann,\rdblquote  she said.\par
He picked her up and hugged her. \ldblquote You\rquote re eight years old now,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You\rquote re a big girl.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t really know how old I am,\rdblquote  she said in a teasing voice, kissing him lightly on the forehead. \ldblquote You\rquote re just guessing.\rdblquote\par
\pard\fi720\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx9291 Johann dropped her to the floor of the cave and stared at his little companion. The light from the torches standing just outside the cave entrance caught the deep blue of her eyes, suddenly reminding Johann of Maria\rquote s mother. There was a powerflil rush of memory and emotion that left him momentarily speechless.\par
\ldblquote What is it, Johann?\rdblquote  Maria said, noticing his change of expression.\par
\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  he replied. \ldblquote You\rquote re right, of course, about your age ... It\rquote s impossible to determine without any true frame of reference.\rdblquote  Johann suddenly brightened. \ldblquote But it doesn\rquote t matter if today is \i really \i0 your birthday, or not,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Because \i we \i0 are going to celebrate anyway ... Wait here for a moment, I\rquote ll be right back.\rdblquote\par
Johann dashed out of the main cave and turned left, into the plaza where the perpetual fire burned. Around be\f1\-\f0 hind the fire, in a barricaded alcove beside one of the smaller caves, he had hidden all of Maria\rquote s birthday presents in a decorated wheelbarrow He removed the barricade, grabbed the handles of the wheelbarrow, and drove it back to the entrance to the cave.\par
\ldblquote All right, young lady;\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote It\rquote s time for your presents.\rdblquote\par
Maria stepped out into the artificial daylight. She re\f1\-\f0 moved the decorative fabric fiom the top of the wheel\f1\-\f0 barrow and began rummaging through her new toys. Each of them had been painstakingly created by Johann during the weeks before her birthday from materials that he had collected from the island and the lake. There was a new; larger abacus, several pieces of furniture for the tiny houses in their make-believe city on the sand beside the lake, a pair of small carved dogs, new costumes for both the Siegfried and Brunhild marionettes that Johann used to illustrate his Wagnerian stories, and three human figurines, about twenty centimeters high, two men and a woman, wearing robes that covered their bodies from just below the neck down to their ankles.\par
The delighted little girl held the three figurines close to her face, so that she could see them more clearly \ldblquote This must be Brother Ravi,\rdblquote  she said after a moment\rquote s exaniuna\f1\-\f0 non. Johann nodded. \ldblquote And these two are Sister Nuba and BrotherJose.\rdblquote\par
Maria carried the figurines into the cave and placed them on a shelf that had been built against the wall behind her bed. On that same shelf were eight other human figu\f1\-\f0 rines, the tallest of which bore a striking resemblance toJo\f1\-\f0 hann. Maria surveyed her collection with satisfaction.\par
\ldblquote I have them all now;\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote You, Mother, Father, Sister Vivien, Kwame, Anna, Fernando, and Satoko, and now these three.\rdblquote  She spun around and ran back toward Jo\f1\-\f0 hann, literally jumping into his arms this time. \ldblquote Thanks again, Johann,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote I could not have asked for better presents."\par
In a few seconds she wriggled out of his arms and re\f1\-\f0 turned to the wheel-barrow to pull out the carved dogs and the doll furniture. \ldblquote Come on,\rdblquote  she said, running off toward the lake. \ldblquote Let\rquote s go play\emdash we can eat the cake later, after lunch.\rdblquote\par
Johann followed her down the path toward the water.\par
