ON THE SAND beside the lake what had originally been built as a small town, named Potsdam after Johann\rquote s boy\f1\-\f0 hood home, had now grown into an extended ciw Con\f1\-\f0 struction on their city in the sand had been ongoing for over a year by the time Johann and Maria celebrated her eighth birthday Their play together in Potsdam offered Jo-hams a perfect means of introducing the girl to a wide range of human endeavors and activities that would have been utterly foreign to her otherwise. The concepts of family, marriage, divorce, school, work, money, and other items that would have been familiar to any normal eight-year-old on Earth meant nothing to Maria, who had never seen any human beings other than Johann. She was fasci\f1\-\f0 nated by his descriptions of the daily lives of the people in their tiny houses, descriptions which Johann, who lacked a fertile imagination, drew completely from his own child\f1\-\f0 hood memories of the people who lived on his block in Kiezstrasse in Potsdam.\par
Potsdam was Maria\rquote s favorite play activity, and time with Johann on the sand in and around their city was often her reward for outstanding performance during the morning school lessons that the girl tolerated only because they were so important to Johann. Maria had little or no interest in spelling, or multiplication tables, or Earth geography, but she did her lessons brilliantly so that she could spend more time sitting beside Johann on the beach and creating a new school complex, or a shopping center, or a residential hous\f1\-\f0 ing development.\par
What thrilled Maria the most during their play were the details of daily life in Potsdam for the people who inhabited their buildings and worked in their offices. Constantly prodded by his young companion for more minutiae about the lives of the citizens in their city, Johann began to recall events from his childhood that he had long since forgotten. Maria took these vignettes from his memory and expanded and embellished them. Thus the day that Johann\rquote s friend Otto temporarily disappeared (in reality there had been a new film that Otto had risked the wrath of his parents to see) became, in Maria\rquote s mind, a family soap opera that ended with Otto\rquote s unconscious body being dragged from the Havel River and miraculously resuscitated.\par
Maria\rquote s precocious imagination, which Johann only fettered when her lack of life experience caused her to concoct a scene or situation that could not possibly have happened, eventually became the driving factor behind\par
their play. It was as much a source of delight for him as it was for her.\par
\ldblquote Mr. Kleinschmidt has made another ten million marks,\rdblquote  she would say \ldblquote and wants to build a new Wagnerian theatre out by the lake.... But he insists that the audiences must have good restaurants available in the immediate vicinity.\rdblquote  She would sketch the general design of the build\f1\-\f0 ings on the sand and then, with Johann\rquote s counsel and engi\f1\-\f0 neering advice, choose the building materials and the sites for the new complex. Maria did not do any of the actual construction. That was Johann\rquote s task. But she would regale him with tales about Mr. Kleinscbmidt, or his daughter Katya who wanted to be an actress but had a speech im\f1\-\f0 pediment, while Johann was adding the new buildings, roads, and trolley tracks to their make-believe city.\par
Several months before her eighth birthday, Johann and Maria\rquote s imaginary abode had changed, at her insistence, to a brand-new house in their Potsdam on the sand. They had moved from Kiezstrasse to a housing development close to the Schloss Cecilienhof and its magnificent lakeside park. In this new neighborhood Johann no longer had his child\f1\-\f0 hood memories to help him recall who lived in what houses. Maria, of course, knew not only the names of the imaginary people who inhabited every one of the little houses spread out on the beach, but also all the details of their lives. She chided Johann when he forgot that Ulrike was the daughter of the Muellers, not the Heinnchs. The play in their city had by this time become completely hers. Johann was only a willing acolyte.\par
According to Maria, one of the most recent families to move into their housing development was from Egypt, like Maria\rquote s father. Both of the parents in the family worked all day Their only daughter, Tetrethe, was lonely She had not yet become friends with the other children in the neighbor\f1\-\f0 hood. Tetrethe wanted a pet. On the day of her birthday, by the tune that Johann reached their re-created city on the sand, Maria had already placed the two carved dogs outside a specific new house at the edge of the city.\par
\pard\fi720\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx9291\ldblquote Tetrethe is happy now,\rdblquote  she shouted as Johann ap\f1\-\f0 proached. \ldblquote When she comes home from school she\rquote ll have someone to play with.\rdblquote\par
She looked up at him innocently and a quizzical look spread across her face. \ldblquote But she wants to know what kind of dogs these are, and I can\rquote t tell her:\rquote\par
\ldblquote The lighter, long skinny one is a dachshund." Johann answered. \ldblquote The other is a schnauzer.\rdblquote\par
Maria explained what she had just learned to the make-believe Tetrethe and then began placing the other pieces of birthday furniture in houses in the same neigh\f1\-\f0 borhood. One of the homes had to have its walls torn down to accommodate a fancy entertainment/communications system. Maria explained to the Offenbachs that now they would be able to have \ldblquote full-screen, interactive entertainment on demand\rdblquote  as a result of their purchase. Jo\f1\-\f0 hann smiled to himself while he was reconstructing the Offenbachs\rquote  house and listening to Maria\rquote s banter. \i She has learned \i0 my \i words well, \i0 he thought, \i even though she has ab\f1\-\f0 solutely no idea what they really mean.\par
\i0 When Johann was finished, Maria looked troubled. \ldblquote While I was talking to Mrs. Offenbach," she said, \ldblquote she told me that her husband, Fritz, has not been feeling well. He is over at the doctor\rquote s office now. Let\rquote s go see what\rquote s the matter with him.\rdblquote\par
Johann and Maria took several steps to the right and Maria dropped down on her knees next to the building marked with a red cross on the top. \ldblquote Oh no, Johann," she said after several seconds. \ldblquote Mr. Offenbach has a brain tumor that must be treated immediately or he will die. What a terrible tragedy that would be for Mrs. Offenbach and their two daughters....\par
