\ldblquote EXCEPT FOR THE events involvingYasin, Vivien said the next evening as the three adults gathered to talk and sip herbal tea around the fire for the third night in a row, \ldblquote his description of what happened to us after your departure with Beatrice was reasonably accurate. Two of those pecu\f1\-\f0 liar snowmen creatures and a ribbon came for us in that waiting room two hours later. We followed the ribbon up the helical slide and then across a long, dark plateau of some kind until we came to a lake. After a four-hour boat ride we landed on a forested shore, where we walked for hours on a narrow path through the trees. Eventually we reached the clearing with the continuous fire and the te\f1\-\f0 pees that became our village home. We lived there until a month ago.\par
\ldblquote At first we \i did \i0 have difficulty organizing ourselves into any kind of a coherent conimunity. In those early days life in our new village was chaotic and stressful. Every\f1\-\f0 body seemed to be in everyone else\rquote s way. Brother Jose and Sister Nuba were both outspokenly critical of me for re\f1\-\f0 nouncing my Michaelite vows so quickly and becoming Kwame\rquote s sexual partner and wife, Yasin fomented contro\f1\-\f0 versy and argument in his own unique way, and poor preg\f1\-\f0 nant Satoko, who could not cope with anything that was happening, was a total mess. After a while, however, when everyone but Yasin began to accept Kwame\rquote s leader\f1\-\f0 ship, the required tasks were divided up among the mem\f1\-\f0 bers of our group and we settled into an acceptable daily rhythm.\rdblquote\par
Vivien lit one of her cigarettes and smiled at Sister Nuba across the fire. \ldblquote Nuba and Jose even apologized to me for having given me so much grief about Kwame.\par
Soon thereafter, Ravi announced that he too was going to renounce his vows and marry Anna Kasper. All in all, our life was fairly good for a couple of months, and all of us ex\f1\-\f0 cept Yasin were making the necessary adjustments to live together in our unusual environment.\par
\ldblquote Then, when it seemed that Satoko\rquote s improved mental condition had finally stabilized, she suddenly took a dra\f1\-\f0 matic turn for the worse. At first none of us suspected that her breakdown might have been caused by a specific event, for Satoko never told us of anything untoward that might have been responsible for her alienation and depression. As time passed, however, we began to notice that her terror and heightened nervousness were always more pronounced when Yasin was around. One evening, while we were talk\f1\-\f0 ing, none of us could account for Yasin\rquote s whereabouts for several hours on the day that Satoko\rquote s breakdown occurred. On subsequent days when Satoko was left by herself in the village and Yasin was assigned solitary work tasks, her con\f1\-\f0 dition was always markedly worse when the rest of us re\f1\-\f0 turned from our hunting and gathering.\rdblquote\par
Vivien finished her cigarette and shook her head. \ldblquote It was stupid of us not to realize earlier what was going on. It just didn\rquote t seem possible to us that any human being could be \i that \i0 depraved. Of course, when Yasin was actually caught in the act of raping Satoko, all of us except Sister Nuba exploded in rage. Our primary concern after Yasin was thrown into the chasm was \i not \i0 what a terrible sin we had collectively committed; we were all worried that the bas\f1\-\f0 tard might somehow have survived the fall because of the low gravity here.\rdblquote\par
Vivien was silent for a long time. \ldblquote Eventually, of course, each of us realized that we had all participated in what we believed at the time to have been a murder. Espe\f1\-\f0 cially to those of us who had spent part of our lives in formal religious training, such a deliberate act of violence seemed unforgivable. Our small village became pervaded by an overwhelming gloom. With all that guilt upon our shoulders, life was very difficult for many weeks. Several of us, including Ravi and me, both of whom had vocally en\f1\-\f0 couraged Kwame and Fernando to kill Yasin, had sustained bouts of terrible depression.\par
\ldblquote Without Brother Jose and Sister Nuba," Vivien said, reaching over and touching Nuba\rquote s hand fondly, \ldblquote we might never have been able to forgive ourselves. But after they both publicly reaffirmed their Michaelite vows, Nuba and Jose declared that we were going to atone for our misdeed by collectively sharing all our feelings about what had hap\f1\-\f0 pened. For weeks they were towers of strength, eventually managing to convince us that God does not demand per\f1\-\f0 fection, just recognition of sin and then expiation.\rdblquote\par
A sound from where the children were sleeping at the opposite end of the cave caused Vivien to turn her head in that direction. She listened intently for a few seconds be\f1\-\f0 fore taking another sip of her tea. \ldblquote A mother\rquote s senses are so keen, Johann,\rdblquote  she then said. \ldblquote I never would have believed it if I hadn\rquote t experienced it myself No matter what we\rquote re doing, we hear every cough, every sleeping moan that our children make. It\rquote s another of God\rquote s miracles\par
Vivien smiled and looked momentarily puzzled. \ldblquote Now where was I?\rdblquote  she said with a short laugh. \ldblquote I\rquote m be\f1\-\f0 coming forgetful in my old age.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The period of atonement after Yasin\rquote s death,\rdblquote  Sister Nuba reminded her.\par
\ldblquote Oh, yes,\rdblquote  Vivien continued. \ldblquote Gradually we all re\f1\-\f0 turned to our former selves and laughter again rang out regularly in our village. I resumed my role as the comic re\f1\-\f0 lief for the group, occasionally sharing some of my more hilarious experiences from my pre-Michaelite days as an escort in London. Sister Nuba and BrotherJose often acted as if they were scandalized by my tales, but more than once I caught them laughing out loud.. . . Satoko gave birth to Keilco without difficulty, and we all joined with Fernando and her in the celebration of the first addition to our com\f1\-\f0 munity. Our existence then became very orderly. Each of us had a prescribed set of duties.\par
\ldblquote After a while, I\rquote ll admit that I started becoming bored by the predictability of our daily routines. Kwame even re\f1\-\f0 ferred to me as a \lquote bitch\rquote  a few times during this period. However, he and the others were saved from my compul\f1\-\f0 sive hunger for variety by a natural event. I became preg\f1\-\f0 nant, and then a mother, and found an infinite outlet for my curiosity and energy.\par
\ldblquote Motherhood transformed me, Johann. After little Beatrice\rquote s birth, I often laughed at the strange odyssey of my life, from high-class whore on Earth to doting mother in an alien sphere. I had never imagined myself being the enthusiastic parent, but there I was, day after day regaling everyone with the newest achievements of my darling daughter.... Meanwhile, R.avi and Anna had a son, Eric, a year younger than Beatrice, and then Anna became preg\f1\-\f0 nant withSerentha less than two months after Kwame and I conceivedJomo.\par
\ldblquote Anna and I became very good friends during our pregnancy together. We would often compare observations on how our thoughts, feelings, and even our dreams changed during pregnancy. At night I would sometimes exult, while rubbing my stomach and feeling my son inside my belly, on the astonishing miracle that is human life. I was happier than I could ever remember being.. . . But Anna and I had to be somewhat circumspect about ourjoy, for poor Satoko had only recently had her second miscarriage and any overheard comments about the delights of pregnancy were virtually certain to send her spiraling off into another de\f1\-\f0 pression.\par
\pard\fi720\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx9291\ldblquote Satoko\rquote s mental health was the only significant prob\f1\-\f0 lem in our community during those years. She knew that Fernando wanted to have a son and obsessively blamed her\f1\-\f0 self for both of the miscarriages. Satoko was so focused on the son she had not yet had that she paid very little atten\f1\-\f0 tion to her daughter. Since Keiko and Beatrice were play\f1\-\f0 mates and friends, it was natural that I became Keiko\rquote s acting mother. Fernando didn\rquote t mind. In fact, he was grateful that I was willing to take some of the parenting burden off his shoulders.\par
\pard\fi720\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx9291\ldblquote When Satoko became pregnant again, and made it successfully through the first trimester\emdash which was when her earlier miscarriages had occurred\emdash we all rejoiced. For the first extended time period since we left Mars, Satoko seemed normal and rational. Fernando was deliriously happy. The whole cornmunity, including Beatrice, Keiko, and Eric, all of whom were now old enough to understand what was happening, participated in the almost daily dis\f1\-\f0 cussions about how Satoko was carrying the child, and what the implications were for the baby\rquote s sex.\par
\ldblquote Sister Nuba had worked extensively with pregnant women at the church in Mutchville and was our resident expert on the sex of unborn children. She had correctly called each of the previous five births. Although she cau\f1\-\f0 tioned us that she could be wrong, the day Sister Nuba in\f1\-\f0 dicated that she thought the next Gomez would be a boycbild, an impromptu party occurred. Kwame and I talked that night, before we fell asleep, about how disap\f1\-\f0 pointed Fernando and Satoko would be if the baby turned out to be a girl. We never even considered a more tin\f1\-\f0 pleasant scenario.\par
Vivien stopped and grimaced. She reached for a ciga\f1\-\f0 rette and lit it before continuing. \ldblquote There are moments in each of our lives that profoundly impact everything that\par
happens from that time forward. Sometimes the signifi\-cance of these moments is clearly understood at the time, such as when I decided to become a Michaelite priestess, or when we all boarded that hatbox waiting on the Martian plateau. But none of us knew, as we looked in sorrow at Satoko and Fernando\rquote s stillborn son, that all of our lives would be irrevocably changed by the child\rquote s death.\par
\ldblquote I have never seen any human being as utterly devas\f1\-\f0 tated as Satoko was by the stillbirth. She emitted a terri\f1\-\f0 fying wail when she realized that she had delivered a dead baby, and even five hours later, when darkness came, her body was still convulsing with her sobs. We attempted to sit up with her during the night, but she kept screaming for all of us, even Fernando, to go away and leave her alone. We finally left her. It was a terrible mistake. The next morning she was gone.\rdblquote\par
Vivien took a final drag on her cigarette and then stubbed it out on a nearby rock. \ldblquote That first morning," she said, \ldblquote we all volunteered to help Fernando with the search..\par
