For the first ten days or so of his conf inement, \f3 Johann\rquote s \f2 loneliness was manageable. He swam, ate, and slept when\-ever he felt like it. He allowed his mind to jump from topic to topic without any overall sense of direction. In general, he was not overly discontent with his life.\par
Soon, however, the purposelessness of his existence began to weigh heavily upon him. Throughout his life, a considerable proportion of his time and energy had always been spent planning for future events and activities. Even when he had been with the family group in the grotto, Jo\-hann had busied himself during a part of every day orga\-nizing \f3 everyone\rquote s activities, \f2 thinking about what he might do with the children, what he wanted to discuss with Nuba, when he might have some private time with Vivien, et cetera. In his current situation, the future was forever like the present. He had no idea how long his confinement would last, and no way of finding out. Any thoughts about the future seemed useless.\par
He began to experience extended periods of abject de\-\par
pression. During these periods Johann did not eat, he did not swim, and he did not really sleep. He would sit and stare for hours at the same spot on the wall, unaware of any thoughts except a longing for his emotional pain to be over. At the end of one such episode\f3  \f2 Johann was surprised to dis\-cover that he had been crying. He could not remember what had prompted the tears, or when they had begun.\par
Johann knew that he would wither away and die if he did not break the cycle of depression. Yet he was powerless against its pervasive grip on him. He tried thinking about Vivien and his unborn child, but his momentary pleasure in conjuring up images of his first son or daughter was de\-stroyed by the realization that he would probably never even see the child.\par
