\i0 SIEGFRIED GREETED HIM \f3 soon after he came down the switchbacks. \ldblquote Father,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote we are missing another bundle of grain. They came across during the night\emdash\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I know,\rdblquote  Johann interrupted his son. \ldblquote I saw someone climbing the path up Black Rock.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Who was it?\rdblquote  Siegfried said, his anger visible. \ldblquote Jomo or that asshole Eric?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I couldn\rquote t tell:\rquote  Johann said. \ldblquote Besides, \f2 it \f3 doesn\rquote t matter. They\rquote re all thieves by association.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Siegfried\rquote s eyes narrowed. \ldblquote That\rquote s the \i\f2 third \i0 time they have stolen food from us. When are we going to do some\-\f3 thing about it?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 The strength of Siegfried\rquote s outrage instantly reminded Johann of an incident from his own youth, when he too was sixteen and idealistic and saw the world in terms of blacks and whites. \i\f2 That was years and years ago, \i0\f3 he thought, pushing aside the memory of his anger after the Bauer brothers had purposely. destroyed Heike\rquote s bicycle. On a \i dif\f2 ferent planet called Earth. In a country named Germany.\par
\i0\f3 Johann put his arm around his son. \ldblquote And what exactly do you think we should do, Siegfried?\rdblquote  he asked. \ldblquote Attack them at night? Steal their children?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Please do not mock me, Father:\rquote  Siegfried said, his feelings hurt. \ldblquote You said yourself that it\rquote s not fair for us to work so hard and for them to reap the benefits of our labor\rquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry; son,\rdblquote  Johann said. \ldblquote You\rquote re right, of course. But it\rquote s not clear what we should do in this situation.... Their crops are a mess. When I examined them from the hills last week, their grain looked sparse and desiccated..."\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Oh, there you are:\rquote  Vivien said, coming up the path to greet her husband and son. Her shoulder-length hair was all gray now, and she walked with a slight limp, but her face was as fresh and smiling as if she were still a teenager.\f2\par
\f3 She greeted Johann with a hug and a brief kiss. \ldblquote I guess Siegfried has already told you?\rdblquote  she said. After Johann nodded, Vivien added, \ldblquote What I can\rquote t understand is why they would \i\f2 steal \i0\f3 from us. Why couldn\rquote t they simply ask us for help?\rdblquote\f2\par
\i Because Maria has too much pride, \i0 Johann thought. \i And the others will not argue with her\f3 .\f2\par
\i0 When Johann offered no response, Vivien decided not to pursue the matter for the moment. The three of them\f3  \f2 walked in silence toward the kitchen, a partially covered wooden shed in the center of the village. Ravi, Anna, and Beatrice were standing together next to a crude, charred pot suspended over an open fire. Steam was rising from the container.\par
Johann glanced down the path at the three who were waiting and sensed from their body language that a group meeting had already been arranged. His good mood of an hour earlier had been shattered by the discovery of the theft. Now what he was feeling was the same sorrowful heartache that usually accompanied his thoughts about Maria. \i\f3 I don\rquote t want to talk about this nght now, \i0\f2 Johann said to himself, abruptly leaving the path and heading toward the ocean.\par
\f3\ldblquote Where are you going?\rdblquote  Vivien asked.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I would like some scruffles for breakfast,\rdblquote  Johann replied, without stopping or turning around.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Siegfried and Serentha picked up three or four dozen already this morning, while you were out swimming,\rdblquote  Vivien said.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I want \i\f2 black \i0\f3 scruffles, from the hollow,\rdblquote  Johann said.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Be careful,\rdblquote  Vivien shouted after a moment\rquote s pause.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote The tide is coming in and Beatrice saw a pair of sperdens just before you came back\rquote\f2\par
