\pard\fi720\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx9291 JOHANN PAUSED NEAR the top of Black Rock Pro\-\f3 montory to take a drink from the trickling creek that dropped out of the hills behind Maria\rquote s village. It had been a long day. He felt mentally and physically exhausted. \i\f2 I grow old, I grow old, \i0 he mused to himself. \i I shall wear the bottoms of my trousers rolled.\par
\i0 The sun was starting to set behind the western moun\-tains. Desiring a break before returning to Vivien and the others, Johann strolled out along the barren rock toward the ocean and sat down on the edge of the cliff In front of him, the endless expanse of ocean was broken only by a solitary slender island, a kilometer or two Qffihore, where he could see the outlines of trees and bushes in the late afternoon sunlight. A couple of hundred meters below him, big waves crashed against the jagged black rocks, sending white spray in all directions.\par
\f3 As the light continued to fade in the west, the stars filled the sky with their splendor, touching Johann with that same combination of joy and awe he had known since he had first examined, the clear night sky as a schoolboy. \ldblquote The stars are your parents,\rdblquote  he could still hear his earnest elementary-school teacher Herr Yeager saying. \ldblquote Every im\f2\-portant element in your body, from the iron in your hemo\-\f3 globin to the calcium in your bones and teeth, was created in the death throes of stars like these and blasted across the galaxy to be present here at that special moment when the Earth first accreted.\rdblquote\f2\par
\i Where is Herr Yeager now? \i0 Johann wondered, his eyes scanning the moonless sky vainly for some clue, perhaps never recognized before, that would identifj for him the Sun that was the home star for his native planet. \i And what would Herr Yeager think\f3  i\f2 f he could have known that those same chemicals created by dying stars had made other ljfe, and other intelligence as well, at djfferent locations and epochs throughout our galaxy?\par
\i0 As his eyes alternately feasted on the star-filled sky and the waves crashing against the rocks below him, Johann thought, as he often did, about the extraordinary sequence of events that had taken him from Germany to Mars to an astonishing spherical alien worldllet and finally to this new planet, located somewhere in the local neighborhood of his Sun, where it appeared it would be his destiny to die. The many amazing scenes from his life swarmed through his mind. He saw again the initial apparition of the particles in the falling snow in the park in Berlin, the ice caverns be\-neath the Martian polar ice, the endless train of suffering humans during his strange boat ride with Sister Beatrice, the blast from the simulated Hiroshima bomb, Beatrice singing love songs to him on the beach in paradise, the mo\-\f3 ment that he killed Yasin, Maria\rquote s birth, Beatrice\rquote s death and astonishing reincarnation as ghost and angel, his masket friend Scarface, the charge of the elevark, the nozzlers and their grotto, and finally, since \f2 it was very much on his mind, his scene with Maria that very afternoon.\par
Overwhelmed by his memories and his feelings, Jo\-\f3 hann stood up on the edge of the promontory and raised his arms to the heavens. \ldblquote But what is \f2 it \f3 all for?\rdblquote  he shouted. \ldblquote When the last human ever to be alive perishes, and never again does this unique combination of chemicals risen to consciousness grace the glories that nature has created, what will have been accomplished? What purpose will we have served?\rdblquote\f2\par
Unaware of the tears now filling his eyes, Johann con\-\f3 tinued to speak to the sky. \ldblquote I do not ask all these questions \f2 for myself, for I have certainly been shown \i my \i0 personal in\-significance in the greater scheme of the universe. But do all of us, taken together, not only every human who has ever lived, but also all those who have not yet been born, \i also \i0 amount to nothing? Will it have been only a com\-\f3 pletely random event that for one brief epoch a strange, sentient, bipedal creature dominated a small, insignificant blue planet orbiting an inauspicious stable yellow star in one of the spiral arms of the galaxy?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3  Johann paced back and forth along the edge of the promontory for several seconds before raising his arms and invoking the sky again. \ldblquote And if none of our activities has any meaning whatsoever, how is it possible that I am so filled with anguish at my inability to bestow happiness upon the child that I have raised and treasured? Why do I strive so hard not just to survive, but to understand this amazing universe that surrounds me? And why do I still miss so desperately one single person whom I loved with \f2 all my being, who filled my life with a glory beyond anything \f3 I could have ever dreamed possible?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3  Johann fell down on his knees, trembling. \ldblquote So tell me God, if You know, and if You exist, how these two com\f2\-pletely inconsistent concepts can possibly both be true? How can absolutely nothing human, past, present, or fu\-\f3 ture, have any meaning at all and yet, at the same time, each and every one of us who lives is touched so much by the miracle of our existence that we feel passionately about the importance of our lives and our actions?\rdblquote\f2\par
Exhausted by his harangue,  Johann fell silent, staring absently at the natural beauty that surrounded him. His dis\-\f3 quiet about Maria and, in fact, all his other worries, had temporarily been dispelled. It was one of the rare moments inJohann\rquote s life when he was at peace with himself.\f2\par
He must have sat on the promontory for an hour be\-fore he reluctantly decided that it was time for him to re\-turn to the West Village and share his news for the day.\par
\f3  Johann stood up, and started walking away from the ocean. As he approached the path that descended to the fields and orchards adjacent to their living area, he turned one last time to look back at the magnificent night sky Off to his left, one of the twin moons, barely a crescent, had just crossed the horizon. But what caught his attention inime\-diately was a new, glowing light, low in the sky off the end of the promontory, that appeared to be growing and moving in his direction.\par
A surge of joy and delight energized  Johann and chased away the weariness he was feeling. He had no doubt that somewhere in that light headed toward him would be his beloved Beatrice.\par
