\f3 Johann churned through the surf with his powerful legs until he was waist deep in the ocean water. Then he plopped down on his stomach and began to swim furiously The black cloud of onrushing doom now obscured the mountains completely The chorus of hideous, threatening noises continued to grow in amplitude, echoing through the twilight with a high\emdash pitched \i\f2 brank, brank, brank \i0 that ter\-rified any living creature who could hear.\par
Johann was about four hundred meters out into the ocean when the first of the branker scouts reached the East Village. Maria, Keiko, and the others looked up at the giant, loathsome, insectlike creature flying into their living area and began to run toward their huts. The branker pirouetted in the sky, screamed \i brank, brank \i0 at another scout hovering over Black Rock Promontory and the pair de\-scended into the village. Only moments later they held Eric, flailing uselessly, in their combined talons about forty meters above the ground and were flying rapidly in a west\-erly direction.\par
Johann saw nothing of this. He was swimming as fast as\f3  \f2 he could away from the mainland, the two papooses strapped to his back. It was not until he felt something sharp tearing into his right thigh that he realized he was being pursued.\par
\f3 Being careful to keep the infants\rquote  heads above the water line, Johann stopped and treaded water. Hovering half a meter above his head was one of the ugliest creatures he had ever seen. At first glance it looked like a monstrously large fruit fly with a pair of sharp talons descending from the front end of its elongated jet-black body. The branker had a double pair of wings which fluttered so fast as \f2 it hov\-\f3 ered that some of the time they could not even be seen. The stronger, broader upper wings, attached to the top of the branker\rquote s body, were over two meters in length. The lower wings, smaller in every dimension, were attached to the bottom of its body; directly under the upper set.\f2\par
\f3 A huge, black, solitary eye filled most of the branker\rquote s head. Under this eye was a gaping dark hole filled with thirty or forty sharp teeth. Its mouth was open continu\f2\-\f3 ously and drooling a white viscous material that fell onto the top of Johann\rquote s head and made him shudder. The branker suddenly turned toward the mainland, apparently deciding \f2 it needed help, and screamed \i brank, brank \i0 in a loud voice.\par
By this time at least three dozen brankers were already scavenging in the East Village. They grabbed everything, not only the human occupants, but also their equipment, food, and anything else that looked noteworthy Maria, Keiko, Satoko, and Jomo were all now airborne and flying toward the west, each a prize claimed by a pair of brankers looking for unusual prey.\par
Johann could not see what was occurring on the main\-land. But he was acutely aware of his own danger. The branker hovering over him repeated its call for help. Johann kept the creature in his sight and did a kind of back-breast\-stroke, moving farther and farther from shore. At length the solitary branker, perhaps irritated because it had not been\f3  \f2 joined by a mate, flew hurriedly away toward the mainland. Johann immediately started swixnniing again, as fast as he could, keeping a close watch on the sky over his head.\par
No more than a minute later a pair of brankers flew out to where Johann was swimming with the infants. Since he was deep in the water, with only his head exposed, the brankers appeared unsure of how to proceed. Suddenly, however, one descended and grabbed each side of \f3 Johann\rquote s \f2 head with one of its powerful talons. Fighting back, Johann pulled the talon off the right side of his face. His effort caused him temporarily to submerge the two babies, who came up sputtering and crying.\par
The sounds of the infants must have surprised the brankers, for they stopped to conduct a lengthy \i brank, brank \i0 conversation while still hovering over the rapidly tiring\f3  \f2 Jo\-hann. Just when they seemed poised for another attack, Jo\-hann heard a familiar frenzied cry and two\f3  \f2 p\f3 air\f2  of \f3 sperdens\f2  struck the brankers from both sides. In the melee that en\-\f3 sued, Johann swam away with the children. He didn\rquote t see who won the battle. But no more \f2 brankers bothered him during his long swim to the island.\par
\par
\par
JOHANN WAS SO tired that he collapsed on the sand as soon as Vivien and Siegfried had removed the papooses from his back The children were fine, considering what they had endured. Vivien reached down to give her prone husband a kiss but he had already dosed his eyes and \f3 fallen asleep. \ldblquote You are a \f2 wonderful man, giant\f3  \f2 Johann," she whispered.\par
From the offihore island Vivien, Siegfried, and Ser\-entha had watched the huge cloud of dark material move into the two villages from the west. Of course, they had had no idea that what they were witnessing was a branker invasion. When, much later, an hour or two before sunrise, they awakened Johann so that he could enjoy the spec\-tacular sight of the setting of the double fullmoom, they\f3  \f2 listened with rapt attention as he described the horde of flying monsters who had descended upon their world.\par
\f3\ldblquote So you don\rquote t think that anyone survived?\rdblquote  \f2 Siegfried asked.\par
Johann shook his \f3 head. \ldblquote I don\rquote t see how \f2 it could \f3 have been possible,\rdblquote  he replied. \ldblquote There must have been a thou\f2\-\f3 sand of those creatures in the first wave alone. As far as I could tell, they attacked everything in sight.\rdblquote\f2\par
Serentha began to cry \f3 Siegfried tried to console herd \ldblquote They didn\rquote t \f2 believe you, Uncle Johann," she kept re\-peating through her tears. \f3\ldblquote And \f2 now both my mother and father are \f3 dead.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote We don\rquote t \f2 know that for \f3 certain,\rdblquote  \f2 Johann said. \f3\ldblquote Let\rquote s \f2 hope they figured out some way to escape.\par
As the Sun rose, down the beach on the far end of the island the hundreds of nepps entered the ocean for the long homeward swim. Scanning the water with his youthful eyes, Siegfried found the formation of the qui\f3 l\f2 led heads, already well out to sea, also heading toward the mainland.\par
\f3\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  \f2 Johann said \f3 to the others, \ldblquote are we \f2 ready to \f3 return?\rdblquote  Siegfried \f2 volunteered to\f3  \f2 p\f3 ull\f2  Serentha and her contrap\-tion as long as Johann would swim behind him in case any\-thing untoward occurred. Vivien helped Johann place the two infants in \f3 their papooses, with Stephanie\rquote s \f2 new neck\-lace carefully packed in her wrappings. There was not much conversation as the preparations concluded. Everyone was thinking about what they would find in their village with a mixture of dread and hope.\par
Any hope they might have had was dispelled when they were close enough to see the remains of the village. Even from out in the ocean a hundred meters away, the total destruction was obvious. The huts had been ripped apart and demolished, the fields and orchards destroyed. Johann and the others somberly trudged onto the beach and began the process of assessing the damage. A few per\-sonal effects were left scattered here and there, apparently\f3  \f2 deemed unimportant by the rampaging brankers, but there were no signs of Ravi, Anna, or Beatrice.\par
\pard\fi720\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx9291\f3\ldblquote They must have been taken away,\rdblquote  Johann said sor\f2\-\f3 rowflilly, \ldblquote along with \f2 our food, our furniture, and most of our \f3 possessions.\rdblquote\f2\par
He put his arms around the weeping Serentha and called for Seigfried and \f3 Vivien to join him. \ldblquote We must re\f2\-\f3 build, of course,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote And this site \f2 still seems to be the best place. We will begin the day \f3 after tomorrow, after we have mourned those we have lost.\rdblquote\f2\par
Siegfried and Serentha went down to the beach to be alone. Johann and Vivien stayed in the area where their community kitchen had been and played with the infants. After half an hour, Johann removed the necklace with the carved amulet from \f3 Stephanie\rquote s papoose \f2 wrappings and started walking toward the east.\par
\f3\ldblquote What are you doing?\rdblquote  Vivien asked gently.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I must go to the East Village,\rdblquote Johann said. \ldblquote If by \f2 any chance Maria is still \f3 alive, I must return this necklace\rquote\f2\par
