\pard\fi720\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx9291\f2 JOHANN WAS DREAMING \f3 about Beatrice. She was wearing her bishop\rquote s robe but they were walking along a beach at night, holding hands. They waded out into the calm, tepid water. She turned to him and he gazed at her magnificent blue eyes. He leaned down to kiss her lips.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Uncle Johann,\rdblquote  he heard a vibrant young girl\rquote s voice say \ldblquote Wake up, Uncle Johann, the sun is about to rise.\rdblquote\f2\par
Johann tried to stay in his dream and savor his kiss with Beatrice. But it was too late. The waking world had already intruded and he could not recapture the intensity of his dream image. He opened his eyes.\par
\f3\ldblquote Good morning, Franzi,\rdblquote  he said. She had the same blue eyes as her great-grandmother. \ldblquote Is \f2 it already time for\f3  our swim?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Yes, Uncle Johann,\rdblquote  she said eagerly. She shook her long hair out of her face. \ldblquote Siegfried and Rowen are waiting down by the creek.\rdblquote\f2\par
Johann sat up slowly on his mat. He winced at the pain in his back and again, when he stood up, at the ache in his right knee. \i Old age is shit, \i0 he thought to himself \i\f3 But as Jar as I know it\rquote s better than \f2 the alternative.\par
\i0 Franzi had left the hut to join the others. Methodically. \f3 Johann placed one more sand pebble in the rightmost of the sheDs lined up against the opposite wall. He didn\rquote t stop to count the pebbles as he had each day during the earlier years. The number of days he had been on this new planet now numbered over ten thousand, and he was well aware \f2 that another double frill moon night was fast approaching. After putting on his trunks, he stumbled outside toward the outhouse, a place he now visited at least once every night during the middle of his sleep.\par
\pard\fi720\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx9291 It was a gray, dreary morning with low clouds and a fine mist. The dampness made Johann feel cold. He shiv\-ered involuntarily. \i Another wonderf\f3 u\f2 l attribute of being old, \i0 he said to himself \i Undue sensitivity to thermal variations.\par
\i0\f3\ldblquote Good morning, Father,\rdblquote  Siegfried said when Johann came out of the outhouse and joined them beside the creek. \ldblquote Did you sleep all right?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote As well as can be expected,\rdblquote  Johann replied. He then smiled. \ldblquote At least I had a couple of good dreams?\rquote\f2\par
The four of them wa\f3 l\f2 ked along the creek toward the switchbacks. Franzi was in front, her long hair cascading down her back, slipping gaily along and whistling to herself Jo\-\f3 hann\rquote s grandson, Rowen, a quiet, contemplative young man in his early twenties, was second in the line. Siegfried, whose hair was now completely gray, walked alongside his father.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote The rocks will be slippery this morning," Siegfried said, \ldblquote so be careful while we\rquote re climbing.\rdblquote\f2\par
Johann chose not to utter the grumpy retort that mime\-diately formed in his mind. Lately it seemed that Siegfried had been treating him more and more like an invalid. True, Johann could no longer work for long stretches in the fields and orchards, but his brain and his hearing were still intact, and his eyesight had not noticeably worsened since their ar\-rival at their new planetary home thirty years ago.\par
\f3 Franzi had already started up the switchbacks, with Rowen not far behind. \ldblquote I\rquote ll bring up the rear,\rdblquote  Siegfried said, motioning for Johann to begin the climb. Johann shot his son an angry glance. \i I won\rquote t \f2 sup and fall, \i0 Johann thought but did not say. \i I have been climbing up this pathfor almost thirty years.\par
\i0\f3 Halfway up the switchbacks, Johann\rquote s heart was pump\f2\-\f3 ing fiercely and he was feeling a little light-headed. He stopped to rest. \ldblquote Are you all right?\rdblquote  Siegfried asked.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Yes, yes, I\rquote m fine,\rdblquote  Johann said. \ldblquote I\rquote ve just been climbing too fast, trying to keep pace with those young\f2\-\f3 sters ahead of us?\rquote\f2\par
\f3 Siegfried stopped, solicitous. \ldblquote Is there anything I can do?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Johann wheeled around. \ldblquote Yes, you can stop treating me as if I\rquote m helpless. Go on, keep walking, catch up with your son. I\rquote m certain the two of you must have plenty to talk about now that we have a nubile female in our group again?\rquote\f2\par
\f3 Siegfried\rquote s eyes flashed. \ldblquote That comment is uncalled for, Father,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You know I have told Rowen that I will not interfere if she chooses him as her first sexual partner\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote That\rquote s what you \i\f2 say," \i0\f3 Johann replied. \ldblquote But your ac\f2\-tions do not support your statements. Your eyes are always following every movement of her body. She sees it. Rowen sees it. \f3 That\rquote s not exactly the best way to snake her feel comfortable?\rquote\f2\par
Instead of answering, Siegfried climbed higher on the path. Johann watched him go and then stretched his right knee, hoping that the ache would go away. \i I have become\par
crotchety and sententious, \i0 he told himself as he began climbing \i again.Just like most old people.\par
\par
\par
\i0 IN SPITE OF \f3 his age, Johann was still the best swimmer among the four of them. Siegfried had more stamina, and Rowen could beat his grandfather in a sprint, but Johann\rquote s effortless stroke and rhythm were still absolutely beautiful to watch.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I wish I could swim like you, Uncle Johann,\rdblquote  the perky Franzi said when they had finished their workout. She was sitting beside him on the grass, her fingers absent\f2\-mindedly twirling the wood amulet at the bottom of her twine necklace.\par
\f3\ldblquote You will someday, if you keep practicing,\rdblquote  Johann replied with a smile. He liked this young girl of fourteen.  She had her great-grandmother\rquote s positive attitude about everything. And she never treated him as if he were old and decrepit.\f2\par
\pard\fi720\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx9291\f3\ldblquote You must have been amazing when you were young, Franzi continued. \ldblquote Uncle Siegfried told me that you were one of the fastest swimmers on Earth\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote That\rquote s a bit of an exaggeration,\rdblquote  Johann said, never\f2\-\f3 theless feeling pride in the girl\rquote s admiration. \ldblquote But I was cer\f2\-\f3 tainly better than most.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Johann\rquote s mind drifted back in time, to a period sixty years earlier in his biological life. He was remembering being the anchor swimmer for Germany in the 4 x 200 freestyle relay in the European Championships. Johann had barely touched out the Italian swimmer to win the gold medal and there had been a jubilant celebration immedi\f2\-ately afterward. For fifteen or twenty seconds he was totally absorbed in his memory, and oblivious to what was occur\-ring around him. When Johann returned to reality, he realized that Franzi was looking at him with a puzzled ex\-pression on her face.\par
\f3\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry;\rdblquote  he said lightly, touching her on the shoulder. \ldblquote I was just thinking about something that hap\f2\-pened a long time ago.. . . We old people do that some\-times. Too many stored memories, I ....... . \f3 Did you ask me a question?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Yes, Uncle Johann,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote I asked if I could go with you to collect the ackyong slime. I\rquote ve never had a chance to go much beyond this lake, and I\rquote ve always wanted to see the geysers, the mudpots, the ackyongs, and the nepps for myself Uncle Siegfried said that \f2 it \f3 won\rquote t be much longer until\emdash\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Of course you can go with me,\rdblquote  Johann interrupted. \ldblquote What a delightful idea. I can\rquote t imagine a greater pleasure than spending a couple of days showing you some of the more interesting sights of our world.\rdblquote\f2\par
\pard\fi720\tx9291\par
\par
\pard\fi720\sl-238\slmult0\qj\tx9291 BOTH SIEGFRIED AND \f3 Rowen were against the idea. \ldblquote Father,\rdblquote  Siegfried said, \ldblquote what has happened to your judg\f2\-\f3 ment? You know your trip could be dangerous. What if you encounter a group of the quilled creatures, as we did sixteen years ago? What if the nepps are not willing to give you processed slime, and you must harvest the ackyong eggs yourself? Franzi has no experience with that kind of situation.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I\rquote m not stupid, Siegfried,\rdblquote  Johann said. \ldblquote I would cer\f2\-tainly take no chances that would endanger the girl. If we encounter something untoward, we will simply return to the ... .. Besides, Franzi \i wants \i0 to go. Our existence here is hardly what a fourteen-year-old girl would call ex\-\f3 citing. She deserves a bit of adventure in her life.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Then I\rquote ll take her,\rdblquote  Siegfried said. He glanced over at his son. \ldblquote And if that makes you nervous, Rowen, you can come along too.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Johann scoffed. \ldblquote You two are ridiculous sometimes.\rdblquote  He turned to Siegfried. \ldblquote Son, you have never established the relationship with the nepps that I have. Four years ago when we went together it was obvious that the nepp leader was not comfortable with you. I am still healthy enough to make the trip, so I should definitely go. \f2 .. . \f3 As for Franzi, I think the nepps will love her. She\rquote ll be unafraid, and play with all the cubs. She\rquote ll be an excellent ambassador.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote And what if something happens to you?\rdblquote  Siegfried asked. \ldblquote Suppose you pass out, as you did two years ago up behind Black Rock Promontory. What will happen to Franzi then? Or worse, suppose you have a heart attack or a stroke? You are a very old man, Father. Franzi would be in an impossible situation if you were incapacitated.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I will make certain before we go that we have very detailed maps,\rdblquote  Johann said in a pained voice. \ldblquote And Franzi will know them by heart before we depart. She will be told that if something serious happens to me, she is to return immediately to the village.\rdblquote\f2\par
\pard\fi720\sl-243\slmult0\qj\tx9291\f3 Johann stood up. \ldblquote This discussion is over,\rdblquote  he an\f2\-\f3 nounced. \ldblquote Sometime next week Franzi and I will visit nep\f2\-\f3 pland and, if we are lucky we will bring back the ackyong slime\rdblquote\f2\par
