JOHANN AND FRANZI ate their first lunch sitting on\f3  \f2 a rock only a couple of meters away from the periodic geyser. Her enthusiasm for everything was infectious. Al\-though he was tired from the climb, Johann felt great. He had just explained to Franzi how water pressure builds up underground, when the geyser suddenly erupted; spraying ajet of water sixty meters into the air.\par
\f3 Franzi jumped up and clasped her hands in excitement. \ldblquote Oh, Uncle Johann,\rdblquote  she exclaimed, watching the water rise to its peak far above her head. \ldblquote I had no idea that it was so beautiful. None of the descriptions have been adequate.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 When the geyser had concluded its eruption, the place from which the water had burst forth had become nothing but an unusual hole in the ground. Gathering all her hair in her hands and holding it behind her head, Franzi lay down and stared into the vent. \ldblquote This is fascinating\rquote  she said.\f2\par
\f3 She came back, sat down next to Johann on the rock, and bit vigorously into a piece of fruit. \ldblquote I want to stay here and see it again," she declared.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote But that will be another hour or so,\rdblquote  Johann said.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Fine\rquote s Franzi said. \ldblquote We\rquote ll just eat our lunch slowly and talL\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Johann laughed and shrugged. \ldblquote As you wish,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote but what would you like to talk about?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Franzi\rquote s face suddenly became serious. \ldblquote Uncle Johann," she said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve never been told the whole story about my parents\rquote  death, just bits and pieces here and there. You promised me once, when I was ten or so, that when I was old enough, you would tell me the entire story Am I old enough now?\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Johann reflected for a moment. \ldblquote I guess so, Franzi,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote But it\rquote s not a happy tale. Are you sure you want to spoil such a superb day by\emdash\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Nothing will be spoiled, Uncle Johann,\rdblquote  the girl in\f2\-\f3 terrupted. \ldblquote I really want to know. Besides, you have always told me that the truth can free us from our unreasonable fears.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Johann finished chewing the piece of fruit that was in his mouth. \ldblquote All right, young lady, if that\rquote s what you want.\rdblquote  He gazed off in the general direction of the ocean, thinking about that terrible, painful day so many years be\f2\-fore. Out of his memory came the indelible images that al\-ways remain with us when we experience a life-altering tragedy.\par
\f3\ldblquote They died on the sixth double full moon night after our arrival here. You were two years old at the time, and your mother was eight months pregnant.\rdblquote  Johann heaved a sigh. \ldblquote I had told both Stephanie and Kwame how impor\f2\-\f3 tant it was that she not be seriously pregnant on a double full moon night, but they ignored my warnings.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 He glanced over at Franzi. \ldblquote Your mother was as head\f2\-\f3 strong as your grandmother Maria. Fortunately, you seem to have inherited more of the temperament of your great-grandmother.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Franzi leaned over and kissed him on the forehead. \ldblquote I know, Uncle Johann,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote You\rquote ve told me that before."\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Anyway,\rdblquote  Johann continued, \ldblquote soon after we went into swimming training it became obvious that there was no way that Stephanie, who was a mediocre swimmer at best, would be able to make it out to the island and back. Vivien was also concerned that too much vigorous exercise in the last trimester might cause a premature birth or other complications. \f2 ... \f3 I couldn\rquote t tow your mother out and \f2 back either, for I had started losing some of my strength, and everyone agreed that I would have my hands full taking care of you.\par
\f3\ldblquote The brankers had not come the previous two double full moon nights and your father, Kwame, had convinced himself that we would be spared on this cycle as well. I pointed out to him that we knew absolutely nothing about what caused the brankers to come, or not to come, and nei\f2\-ther did the nepps. The little guys \i always \i0 prepared for the brankers, and it seemed prudent for us to do the same thing.\par
\f3\ldblquote Prior to thefifth double fall moon night, we had dis\f2\-\f3 covered a cave complex, actually not too far from here, in the hills on the other side of the volcanic rock. Vivien was unable to swim that time, for she had seriously injured her hip while running from a pursuing ackyong. After great deliberation, we concluded that it would be best if she spent the fifth double full moon night down in one of the caves. Since the brankers did not come at all that cycle, we had no way of knowing if it was a safe haven or not.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Johann stopped and remained silent for a long time. \ldblquote When the sixth double full moon night arrived, Vivien de\f2\-cided to spend the night in the caves with your mother. The plan \i m\f3 i\f2 ght \i0\f3 have worked. We just don\rquote t know because..\f2\par
\f3 Johann\rquote s thoughts began to drift again. In his mind\rquote s eye he was again swimming in the turbulent ocean, with Franzi in a papoose strapped to his neck, leading what was left of his family out toward the offihore island that repre\f2\-\f3 sented safety from the brankers. He could still remember Siegfried\rquote s shouts, turning around in the water, and discov\f2\-ering, to his horror, that Kwame was no longer behind them and had swum back toward the mainland.\par
\f3 After a long pause he looked at Franzi and heaved a deep sigh. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry\rdblquote  he said, struggling with his feelings. \ldblquote This is hard for me\rquote\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote I understand, Uncle Johann,\rdblquote  the girl said softly.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote Kwame and I had accompanied your mother and Vivien,\rdblquote  Johann eventually continued, \ldblquote to the cave area and helped them pick out a place to hide. We had left them maps carved on wood that they could read with their finger\f2\-tips in case they needed to find their way out in the dark. Then the rest of us returned to the village and ate a small lunch before we began our swim.\par
\f3\ldblquote It was a stormy day. The waves were much higher than usual. Several groups of nepps and a formation of the quilled creatures were already in the water before us. As planned, I was in the lead with you in a papoose, followed by Siegfried, Rowen, who was only eleven at the time, and then your father.\f2\par
\f3\ldblquote You know, of course, that somewhere during the swim your father, without saying anything to the rest of us, turned around and headed back toward shore. When I heard Siegfried\rquote s shout and swam over next to him in the water, he was furious. He kept pointing at the Sun, and telling me that Kwame was going to lead the brankers to your mother and Vivien. To this day he believes that both his mother and yours would still be alive if Kwame had not returned to the mainland.\rdblquote\f2\par
\f3 Johann sighed again. \ldblquote What actually happened in and around those caves that night is complete speculation. The brankers did come, again reducing our village to rubble. When Vivien, Stephanie, and Kwame were nowhere to be seen after we returned from the island, I left Siegfried in the village with Rowen and you and went to search the caves. Where they had been hiding I found only two objects, Vivien\rquote s little hat that she sometimes wore as a joke, and that amulet now around your neck, which your mother ha\f2 d placed on a rock ledge.\par
\f3\ldblquote So what happened? Did the brankers find your mother and Vivien on their own? Or did your father inad\f2\-\f3 vertently lead them to where the women were hidden? We\rquote ll never know Siegfried, who was very close to his mother, is convinced that your father was responsible for Vivien\rquote s death. But there\rquote s no way we can ever learn the truth."\par
